One year ago, legislation was signed to establish Juneteenth as a national holiday, marking the end of slavery in the United States. It is a day to reflect on the past and look towards a brighter future. The article emphasizes the importance of not just commemorating Juneteenth, but also taking action to deliver on the promise of equality. The current administration is committed to advancing equity and racial justice, addressing systemic racism, and promoting economic opportunity, education, healthcare, voting rights, police reform, and access to justice for Black communities. The article calls for celebration, education, and action on Juneteenth to continue efforts towards a more equitable society.